    <name>Lunar Prospector</name>
    <type>Spacecraft</type>
    <naif_host_id>LP</naif_host_id>
    <description>The Lunar Prospector (LP) is a compact and simple spin-stabilized spacecraft, weighing 305 kg and powered by solar cells and a rechargeable NiCd battery for night operations. It features a spacecraft bus made of graphite-epoxy, with multiple science instruments mounted on three booms, including a Gamma Ray Spectrometer, Neutron Spectrometer, Alpha Particle Spectrometer, Magnetometer, and Electron Reflectometer. The communication system includes an S-band transponder and various antennas, enabling data downlink rates of up to 3600 bps. The spacecraft has a clock that resets annually, and its coordinate system is defined based on the separation plane from its launch stage.
 
 The Deep Space Network (DSN), managed by NASA's Jet Propulsion Laboratory, facilitates two-way communication between Earth and spacecraft, comprising three complexes globally distributed. These complexes have multiple antennas and play a crucial role in radio science investigations.
 
 The Lunar Prospector hosts five scientific instruments to study the lunar environment, along with additional tracking systems for gravity measurements and attitude determination.</description>
